Gentlemen and Ladies.  When I proposed this thread, it was with the thinking that there are many others out there who don't post, don't connect, but also suffer with us, in our pain, our anger, our frustration, and our rage.<br><br>
My e-mails from the &quot;silent&quot; posters have proven my thinking.  My e-mails from most of you have helped me understand and grow that much more.  <br><br>
Doc Del, and others, you don't have to give up your name. Your thoughts and feelings are by far more important to those who listen and read, but won't join.  <br><br>
To those who have written me (electronically), I ask you to post your queries. That way we all share and grow.<br><br>
To Alex and Art, who seem to never be able to get over me, please remember, I can't help being who I am. I pose global thoughts seeking global answers, not personal attacks.  I pose critical thinking concepts, like can a bad war produce good medals, not as a personal thing, but as a global thing.<br>
I ask for honest thought, not quick anger and unthinking responses.  <br><br>
The depth of intellectual dialogue on this site is wonderful. Sadly, the need to attack anyone who might be deemed a thread is not.  <br><br>
The sum total of Vet.Nam Vet's that I have known or worked with, both as patients or associates, is that a certain sense of humor is missing.  Why don't we chew on that, instead of attacking each other?  WW2 vets were in a winning war and got 2 months to de compress after the war. Viet Vets were on a &quot;losing&quot; effort and got 48 hours, if lucky, to adjust to &quot;normal&quot; america.  That ain't funny. But it is reality.  It's now 30 years later.  Do we need to keep attacking each other, or get on with understanding each other.  Hey Alex, Tom Dier, Art V., I'm talking to you!<br><br>
doc
